@GRMIDX{{index="@HI{{keredomo}}" grammar="@HI{{keredomo}}"}}

<body>

<h1>@HI{{keredomo}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Splain{{}} @EM{{@HI{{keredomo}}}}
<li> @Vru{{}} @EM{{@HI{{keredomo}}}}
<li> @Vta{{}} @EM{{@HI{{keredomo}}}}
<li> @Ai{{}} @EM{{@HI{{keredomo}}}}
<li> @Anastem{{}}@HI{{da}} @EM{{@HI{{keredomo}}}}
<li> @N{{}}@HI{{da}} @EM{{@HI{{keredomo}}}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{keredomo}}}} is a isjunctive subordinate conjunction that joins two sentences.
the basic meaning is "although."

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{bamboo^inside}}san'ni@KJ{{electricity^tale}}wokaketa@EM{{keredo}}
      @KJ{{detain^guard}}deshita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I phoned Takeuchi but she was out.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kono@KJ{{book}}ha@KJ{{tall}}i@EM{{keredomo}}ii@KJ{{book}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Although this book is expensive, it's a good book.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>

<p>
At the end of a sentence @EM{{@HI{{keredomo}}}} implies something exists that qualifies what is actually said.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{tamaniha@KJ{{trip^going}}nimo@KJ{{going}}kitaito@KJ{{think}}tteirundesu@EM{{kedo}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I'd really like to go on a trip once in a while (but I don't have the time).
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{keredomo}}}} can be used to delimit a preliminary remark.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{mada@KJ{{departure^shoot}}made1@KJ{{time^interval}}mouarimasu@EM{{kedo}},
      doushimashouka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      There's still an hour until the departure, so what shall we do?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
Another usage of @EM{{@HI{{keredomo}}}} at the end of a sentence is to emphasise that the speaker
wants things to turn out as stated.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{early}}ku@KJ{{warmth}}kakunarutoiinda@EM{{kedo}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      It would be nice if it got warm soon.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
In @S1{{}}@EM{{@HI{{keredomo}}}}@S2{{}}, @S1{{}} is a subordinate clause and is usually in the plain form.
However, in very polite speech @S1{{}} can be in the polite form.
</p>

<p>
@EM{{@HI{{keredomo}}}} has a number of informal forms. In decreasing order of formality
these are @HI{{keredo}}, @HI{{kedomo}} and @HI{{kedo}}.
</p>

